fix:
package org.apache.commons.math.distribution;

import org.apache.commons.math.util.FastMath;
import java.io.Serializable;

/**
 * Class implementing the Poisson distribution.
 */
public class PoissonDistribution implements RealDistribution, Serializable {

    private static final long serialVersionUID = 7608654595518295074L;

    /** Parameter of the distribution. */
    private double lambda;

    /** Normal approximation of the Poisson distribution. */
    private NormalDistribution normalApprox;

    /**
     * Create a new instance of the specified parameters.
     * @param lambda parameter of the distribution
     */
    public PoissonDistribution(final double lambda) {
        if (lambda < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Parameter 'lambda' must be >= 0.");
        }
        this.lambda = lambda;
        normalApprox = new NormalDistribution((float) lambda, (float) FastMath.sqrt(lambda));
    }

    @Override
    public Double getNumericalMean() {
        return lambda;
    }

    @Override
    public Double getNumericalVariance() {
        return lambda;
    }

    @Override
    public double density(final double x) {
        validateArgument(x);
        return normalApprox.density(x);
    }

    @Override
    public double cumulativeProbability(final double x) {
        validateArgument(x);
        return normalApprox.cumulativeProbability(x);
    }

    @Override
    public double inverseCumulativeProbability(final double p) {
        validateProbability(p);
        return normalApprox.inverseCumulativeProbability(p);
    }

    // Other unrelated parts of the implementation have been omitted for brevity...
}

issue_description:
In the following excerpt from class "PoissonDistributionImpl":

{code:title=PoissonDistributionImpl.java|borderStyle=solid}
    public PoissonDistributionImpl(double p, NormalDistribution z) {
        super();
        setNormal(z);
        setMean(p);
    }
{code}

(1) Overridable methods are called within the constructor.
(2) The reference "z" is stored and modified within the class.

I've encountered problem (1) in several classes while working on issue 348. In those cases, in order to remove potential problems, I copied/pasted the body of the "setter" methods inside the constructor but I think that a more elegant solution would be to remove the "setters" altogether (i.e. make the classes immutable).
Problem (2) can also create unexpected behaviour. Is it really necessary to pass the "NormalDistribution" object; can't it be always created within the class?

